Typically more (wider) in the middle, then compress toward the end!
Typical pattern
Input:    784  (e.g. 28×28 image)
Layer 1:  1024  ↑ expand
Layer 2:  512   ↓ compress
Layer 3:  256   ↓ compress
Output:   10    (classes)

Why expand first?
Remember your point — we need neurons to detect many different combinations of inputs. More neurons = more combinations can be represented simultaneously.
784 input features → could have thousands of useful combinations
→ expand so you have enough neurons to detect them all

Why compress later?
Later layers are building higher level abstractions:
Layer 1: 1024 neurons detecting edges, textures
Layer 2: 512  neurons detecting shapes (fewer shapes than edges)
Layer 3: 256  neurons detecting objects (fewer objects than shapes)
Output:  10   final classes
As you go deeper, concepts get more abstract and fewer in number.

But there's no hard rule

The layer size is a hyperparameter we tune. Too narrow = not enough combinations representable. Too wide = wasteful redundancy you identified. Finding the sweet spot is more art than science honestly.